Open],ExpressionUUID -> "198ae807-84a8-4c06-b09e-3f7147ae0d90"],Cell[
TextData[{"Both models reproduce the overall distance\[Dash]redshift trend in the Pantheon+ data. The fixed-parameter FLRW reference yields a lower ",Cell[
BoxData[
FormBox[SuperscriptBox["\[Chi]","2"],TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID -> "1841232c-2e11-254f-a36a-404c3e24c93d"],", while PME achieves a one-parameter kinematic fit once the acceleration scale is externally fixed by the BTFR."}],
"Text",CellChangeTimes -> {{3.9797410622285175`*^9,3.9797411365772476`*^9},{3.980088741035698`*^9,3.9800887685255604`*^9},3.9801579687360935`*^9,3.980158055408844`*^9,3.9803639921806755`*^9,{3.9803647570088863`*^9,3.98036477177903`*^9}},
ExpressionUUID -> "bfcf7b93-3846-da4e-b1d4-9dc5f3483226"],Cell[
"\<However, the difference is structural, not numeric. In FLRW, the expansion history is governed primarily by free density parameters. In PME, the same large-scale behavior is a direct consequence of the manifold kinematics.\>",
"Text",CellChangeTimes -> {3.9801579978579865`*^9,{3.980281262961708`*^9,3.980281264352188`*^9},{3.98028132477516`*^9,3.98028132627487`*^9},{3.980363999226019`*^9,3.980364015008028`*^9},{3.9803647947892056`*^9,3.980364824571062`*^9},{3.9803648762738457`*^9,3.9803648931862564`*^9},3.980365686117073`*^9,3.981804750128851`*^9},
ExpressionUUID -> "d968cb60-e9be-9f43-ae66-321b5ed88b85"]},Open],ExpressionUUID -> "ee4b68dc-8d43-459e-8704-13ed383a551c"]},
Open],ExpressionUUID -> "1678be23-cfac-41af-b548-80744f4116fa"],Cell[
CellGroupData[
{Cell[
"\<Conclusion\>","Section",CellChangeTimes -> {{3.979408374796034`*^9,3.9794083769420185`*^9}},
ExpressionUUID -> "1776a081-6660-45a8-998d-747c74b4847f"],Cell[
TextData[{"In this work we have presented a reconstruction of gravitational dynamics grounded in kinematics rather than force, curvature, or action at a distance. Within the Parabolic Expansion Model, a universal kinematic deceleration of fixed magnitude ",Cell[
BoxData[
FormBox["A",TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID -> "3de2b063-f3ee-9d4c-9bdd-4ac1987f861e"]," emerges as a global property of the manifold. Acceleration Flux Theory identifies this deceleration as a conserved bilocal quantity that exists independently of matter and persists across all scales."}],
"Text",CellChangeTimes -> {{3.979408384074049`*^9,3.9794084300890884`*^9},3.9795649721496487`*^9,{3.981726533143715`*^9,3.98172654148543`*^9}},
ExpressionUUID -> "bdce6192-0b37-4344-a7d0-57a38018355a"],Cell[
"\<Matter does not generate gravitational acceleration, nor does it deform spacetime. Instead, baryonic structure redistributes an ambient background acceleration scale, concentrating flux and producing spatial gradients. In the local bound regime this redistribution yields an inhomogeneous acceleration component obeying a Gauss-type constraint that reproduces the familiar inverse-square behavior associated with Newtonian gravity. The resulting local acceleration,\>",
"Text",CellChangeTimes -> {{3.9794084413139095`*^9,3.9794084756374226`*^9},3.9795649347986984`*^9,3.9817265513867073`*^9},
ExpressionUUID -> "29d8a3d6-4615-7a43-ad32-bfc9eeb9e5ce"],Cell[
BoxData[RowBox[{Cell[
TextData[
Cell[
BoxData[FormBox[RowBox[{RowBox[{SubscriptBox["a","in"],"(","r",")"}],"=",RowBox[
{RowBox[{"-","A"}],"-",FractionBox[RowBox[{"GM","(","r",")"}],SuperscriptBox["r",
"2"]]}]}],TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID -> "33e81b21-34bc-1549-ab0a-ef85317fb324"]],
ExpressionUUID -> "90d1ca93-d913-494d-bac1-6a5529173fd7"],","}]],"DisplayFormula",
CellChangeTimes -> {{3.9793992013571815`*^9,3.979399249519516`*^9}},ExpressionUUID -> "0c7abb06-13b5-6c45-870f-3d035b191550"],Cell[

"\<arises without invoking forces, potentials, or nonlocal interactions.\>","Text",
CellChangeTimes -> {{3.9794085182933846`*^9,3.9794085353432465`*^9}},ExpressionUUID -> "cda89ede-760a-a146-a87a-d3d614f0755e"],Cell[

"\<Within this framework, momentum is not exchanged through forces acting between distant bodies. Momentum change is the local, observable response of mass to a structured acceleration flux. Newton\[CloseCurlyQuote]s second law is retained operationally but reinterpreted: it describes how matter couples to an existing background acceleration scale rather than how bodies exert forces upon one another. Conservation of momentum follows from conservation of acceleration flux under redistribution, replacing action\[Dash]reaction pairs with flux balance.\>",
"Text",CellChangeTimes -> {{3.9794085419142056`*^9,3.9794085930119057`*^9},3.9794090693614826`*^9,3.9795649364862747`*^9,3.979564991970207`*^9,3.98172656686817`*^9},
ExpressionUUID -> "78278b08-50cc-b944-8c25-3f40ce4af834"],Cell[
"\<This construction resolves a long-standing conceptual tension in classical gravity. Newton\[CloseCurlyQuote]s laws successfully describe motion but provide no physical account of how gravitational influence is transmitted. Acceleration Flux Theory supplies that missing mechanism while preserving the empirical content of Newtonian dynamics. In doing so it also exposes the limitation of Newton\[CloseCurlyQuote]s first law: inertial motion is not fundamental but an approximation that neglects a universal background acceleration. Objects at rest do not remain at rest; they evolve under a persistent kinematic acceleration scale whose effects appear once acceleration is treated as primary.\>",
"Text",CellChangeTimes -> {{3.979408608558758`*^9,3.979408633121153`*^9},{3.9794086825229855`*^9,3.979408709793829`*^9},{3.9794090803400993`*^9,3.9794090889493446`*^9},{3.979563444345684`*^9,3.979563454502121`*^9},{3.979565656221077`*^9,3.9795656623003864`*^9},3.9817265769169617`*^9},
ExpressionUUID -> "ed73ce23-f036-9a47-9acc-f0fcbb416953"],Cell[
"\<Gravity therefore emerges not as a force and not as geometry, but as the organized redistribution of a conserved background acceleration scale. The same kinematic structure that governs cosmic expansion also governs local attraction, unifying gravitational phenomena across scales without additional assumptions or dark sectors. Acceleration Flux Theory thus provides a physically intelligible, local, and deterministic foundation for gravity\[LongDash]one that resolves several longstanding conceptual difficulties, including action at a distance, dynamical spacetime curvature, and the separation between cosmic expansion and local gravitational attraction, while remaining fully compatible with observed dynamics.\>",
"Text",CellChangeTimes -> {{3.979408719324541`*^9,3.979408740855385`*^9},{3.9794087709182396`*^9,3.9794087789662094`*^9},{3.979409415966614`*^9,3.9794094322456875`*^9},3.9795649381731567`*^9,3.981726606015461`*^9},
ExpressionUUID -> "41b9b57b-7892-8e4f-accc-1dc15606a280"]},Open],ExpressionUUID -> "a6982fe4-2147-4e87-ab6d-1887b58d0d5c"]},
Open],ExpressionUUID -> "6d058f37-b5cc-4c90-8248-d8341793392a"]},StyleDefinitions -> Notebook[
